                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">It doesn't actually take much money although it will take a cuple of guys to be successful in lowering the amount of player auctions. You pay guys to create many seller/buyer accounts and they will start selling highly desirable items. You then slap warnings on all accounts that have bought items. It's not like you have to worry about the "spies" being recognized since you can change the ingame account names at any time you want. At the same time you have the same guys buy items from others and do the same thing. Give them warnings. Next, on the login splash screen you make a huge announcement that anyone else caught will be banned for one month for buying items and will be banned for good if they are caught selling items. There will be a drastic reduction in player auctioned sales after that. 
<br />

<br />
Yes, you lose some customers when you inevitably have to ban them. Make public announcements of how many are banned each month. This will scare enough players from buying and selling that they will not be auctioning their items or buying items off auctions. It's a FUD tactic really. Yes, they will likely lose a few thousand per month but I bet you in the long run it will be more worth it. I mean, how many of us have hated how the economy in EQ was screwed up by these peope buyihng up everything that was already overpriced and then jacking it up even higher. It was one of the reasons I rarely bought anything in the bazaar except some tradeskill materials and some lower priced items that were only a few k's.
<br />

<br />
And if they really wanted to stop player auctions they could have included flags on all items that hold the last 5 people who had possession of it. I bet you will find that 80% of the items sold will pass through a few accounts who work for the auction places. It's not the small fish you want, it's the big fish. They can just poll the item database for the most common names that have sold/bought items and monitor those accounts. They could do it during update times when the servers are brought down anyways. The big fish are the ones who fubar player economies in games and screw everything up.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">On the other hand, if your reaction to something I say boils down to "You didn't choose MY side, make MY choice," well, you're not looking for information, you're looking for someone to tell you how smart you are thinking the way you do. --</span> <span style="font-weight: bold">Ed Stroligo</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
