                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Manizeh wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Bottom line, there is NO WAY to know if a player gave something to another for free or for RL cash, NONE. Unless, they hack on PA or the credit card companies' database (Both of them illegal. As it is lying under oath).</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Wrong.  And wrong.
<br />

<br />
Ok.  Your assumption is that MMORPG Game Publisher, which knows and controls every inch of code within in their online game, has no ability to track transactions and account information within the game to such a degree that it can know who is recieving big in-game stuff, for example, 100,000 plat or 200 gold at a time, depending on the game, who's giving it, who they are, what their account information, how many similar transactions have occured, etc. etc. etc.?  And that the publisher could not track this information to identify transactions that violate the games EULA?  And that the publisher cannot ever then investigate those transactions, tossing aside, for example, in guild transactions, but giving a closer look to the level 1 toon that has a small fortune in its bank?  That the publisher cannot track changes in account information and posts of people trying to sell toons and correlate that information?  How many players would be happy to sustain closer scrutiny of big transactions and changes in account information in exchange for actual enforcement of rules against ebaying?
<br />

<br />
The bottom line is, the publishers do not need to go to court.  They control the code. 
<br />

<br />
Also, a click within website contract of adhesion with a box that says "yes" is not a statement under oath.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=646635" target="_blank" class="postlink">Saediien Iluvatri</a>
<br />
Retired Coercer of The Rathe
<br />
Saed - Mage - Blackhand - &lt;Drifters&gt;
<br />
Saediien - Druid - Stormrage - &lt;Guardians of Paradise&gt;</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
