<br />
You are right, it is not consider lying under oath legally wise, but it is still lying. 
<br />

<br />
I am no lawyer, but a company that not only lies but presents proof of their lying on court is not gonna look very "innocent" in the eyes of the judge or the jury, on top of stupid (but stupidity is no crime).
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Ok. Your assumption is that MMORPG Game Publisher, which knows and controls every inch of code within in their online game, has no ability to track transactions and account information within the game to such a degree that it can know who is recieving big in-game stuff, for example, 100,000 plat or 200 gold at a time, depending on the game, who's giving it, who they are, what their account information, how many similar transactions have occured, etc. etc. etc.? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
No. I am saying that there is NO WAY for Blizzard to determine whether someone received an item or a character as a gift or not, NONE. I will give you examples.
<br />

<br />
> GM_01 tells you "Hmm... where did you get that 1 million gold all of the sudden?"
<br />
> You tell GM_01 "Some high level guy came and gave it to me after I asked him questions about how to play my character. He said he was leaving the game"
<br />

<br />
Another day...
<br />

<br />
>GM_02 tells you "Where did you get that nice sword?"
<br />
> You tell GM_02 "Some high level guy came and gave it to me after I asked him questions about how to play my character. He said he was leaving the game"
<br />
>GM_02 tells you "Wasnt that the guy that gave you 1 million plat? GM_01 told me about that. We are watching you closely now"
<br />
> You tell GM_02 "Oh, thats very kind of you because my sense of direction is crappy and I get lost all the time, and never find my corpse either. I will not hesitate to send you or GM_01 tells for assistance since you already watching me. Thx"
<br />
> You tell GM_02 "And no, it was a different guy. I think he was leaving the game also, but maybe you and GM_01 are right and he was just rerolling another character. I have never seen him after that though"
<br />

<br />
>GM_03 tells you "Did you buy this character? The account information is different"
<br />
>You tell GM_03 "No. A friend of mine quit the game and gave me the account. I read and understood the EULA rules and I agreed to the terms"
<br />

<br />
The following text is copy pasted from Blizzard EULA rules:
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">You may permanently transfer ownership of the Game and all parts thereof, and all of your rights and obligations under the License Agreement, to another by physically transferring the CD-ROM, all original packaging, and all Manuals or other documentation associated with the Game, and by removing from all of your home or personal computers and destroying any remaining materials concerning the Game in your possession or control, provided the recipient agrees to the terms of this License Agreement.</span>
<br />

<br />

<br />
EDIT: 1 more example.
<br />

<br />
> GM_04 tells you "You have received several high level items and a very high amount of gold several times in the last 30 days. Did you buy the items and money online? Else, how do you explain this?"
<br />
> You tell GM_04 "I have many friends. Doesnt everyone?"</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Manizeh on Mon Jan 24, 2005 11:41 am; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
